File: Eight deaths were reported in the Western Cape, two in the Eastern Cape, one in KwaZulu-Natal and one in the North West. JOHANNESBURG - The North West reported its first COVID-19 death. The number of fatalities rose by 12 to reach 206. Health Minister Zweli Mkhize released the latest numbers on Monday afternoon during a visit to the Eastern Cape. READ: South Africa's COVID-19 cases surpass 10,000 The minister said eight deaths were reported in the Western Cape, two in the Eastern Cape, one in KwaZulu-Natal and one in the North West. A total of 10,652 people have tested positive for COVID-19 in South Africa. Mkhize said about 8 million people have been screened countrywide. READ: Up to 190,000 could die in Africa if virus containment fails: WHO The number of recoveries now stand at 4,357. South Africa is the worst-hit country in sub-Saharan Africa. Since 1 May, the government has gradually eased the confinement measures put in place in late March to stem the spread of the virus. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.